    {
      "id": "3ef4feff208e7ed03023ab1d89f7d36b5f59ae81",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2021-06-14 15:55:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "81b52b8455be03d5cf9949110d2e1c21c15cc772",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2021-06-17 16:47:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIt would be nice if we could somehow reflect the fact that the fatal flag is set in the health value itself (like setting it to zero). That way when an admin checks health with lnetctl net show then they'd see the interface is not really healthy. maybe it'd be sufficient to just print the fatal status in the \"health stats\" section? Or maybe it'd be better to integrate the fatal flag into the NI status?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "76a0ae47d06e8d7ba61e3ff0346406af6c3cbe03",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 824,
        "name": "Serguei Smirnov",
        "email": "ssmirnov@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "ssmirnov"
      },
      "date": "2021-06-17 16:51:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> It would be nice if we could somehow reflect the fact that the\n > fatal flag is set in the health value itself (like setting it to\n > zero). That way when an admin checks health with lnetctl net show\n > then they'd see the interface is not really healthy. maybe it'd be\n > sufficient to just print the fatal status in the \"health stats\"\n > section? Or maybe it'd be better to integrate the fatal flag into\n > the NI status?\n\nSetting NI health to 0 on fatal error would also require setting it back to max when the error is cleared. Integrating fatal flag in NI status is a better option in my opinion. There should be some way to indicate that NI is down due to fatal error.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "65a314b6f7622922ab5cd3f960ad81056dcd5859",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2021-06-17 18:57:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Setting NI health to 0 on fatal error would also require setting it\n > back to max when the error is cleared. Integrating fatal flag in NI\n > status is a better option in my opinion. There should be some way\n > to indicate that NI is down due to fatal error.\n\nI agree that makes the most sense. FWIW, the monitor thread on a router already checks for the fatal flag on its local NIs and sets NI status appropriately (and will push that out if there is a status change). We could refactor that logic, or duplicate the relevant parts of it, so that this check is performed on all peers (though I don't know that we want to be pushing status update for non-router peers).\n\nSee lnet_update_ni_status_locked()",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
